<P>In cryptography, <B>SHA-1</B> is a <A title=3D"Cryptographic hash =
function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_hash_function">cryptog=
raphic=20
hash function</A> designed by the United States <A=20
title=3D"National Security Agency"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Security_Agency">National =
Security=20
Agency</A> and published by the United States <A=20
title=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_=
Technology">NIST</A>=20
as a U.S. <A title=3D"Federal Information Processing Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing_Stand=
ard">Federal=20
Information Processing Standard</A>. SHA stands for "<A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"Secure hash algorithm"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_hash_algorithm">secure hash=20
algorithm</A>". The four SHA <A title=3DAlgorithm=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm">algorithms</A> are =
structured=20
differently and are distinguished as <I>SHA-0</I>, <I>SHA-1</I>, <I><A=20
title=3DSHA-2 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A></I>, =
and <I><A=20
title=3DSHA-3 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-3">SHA-3</A></I>. =
SHA-1 is=20
very similar to SHA-0, but corrects an error in the original SHA hash=20
specification that led to significant weaknesses. The SHA-0 algorithm =
was not=20
adopted by many applications. SHA-2 on the other hand significantly =
differs from=20
the SHA-1 hash function.</P>
<P>SHA-1 is the most widely used of the existing SHA hash functions, and =
is=20
employed in several widely used applications and protocols. In 2005,=20
cryptanalysts found attacks on SHA-1 suggesting that the algorithm might =
not be=20
secure enough for ongoing use.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-2 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-2"><SPAN>[</SPAN>2<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
NIST required many applications in federal agencies to move to <A =
title=3DSHA-2=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A> after 2010 because =
of the=20
weakness.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-3 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-3"><SPAN>[</SPAN>3<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
Although no successful attacks have yet been reported on SHA-2, they are =

algorithmically similar to SHA-1. In 2012, following a long-running =
competition,=20
NIST selected an additional algorithm, Keccak, for standardization as <A =

title=3DSHA-3 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-3">SHA-3</A><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-4 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-4"><SPAN>[</SPAN>4<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-5 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-5"><SPAN>[</SPAN>5<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
