places;<BR><I>n</I> varies for each operation;<BR>W<SUB>t</SUB> is the =
expanded=20
message word of round t;<BR>K<SUB>t</SUB> is the round constant of round =

t;<BR><A class=3Dimage title=3DAddition=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Boxplus.png"><IMG =
alt=3DAddition=20
src=3D"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/75/Boxplus.png" =
width=3D11=20
height=3D11></A> denotes addition modulo =
2<SUP>32</SUP>.</DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>SHA-1 produces a 160-bit <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Message =
digest"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Message_digest">message digest</A> =
based on=20
principles similar to those used by <A title=3D"Ron Rivest"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Rivest">Ronald L. Rivest</A> of =
<A=20
title=3D"Massachusetts Institute of Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technolog=
y">MIT</A>=20
in the design of the <A title=3DMD4=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD4">MD4</A> and <A title=3DMD5=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A> message digest =
algorithms, but=20
has a more conservative design.</P>
<P>The original specification of the algorithm was published in 1993 as =
the=20
<I>Secure Hash Standard</I>, <A title=3D"Federal Information Processing =
Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing_Stand=
ard">FIPS</A>=20
PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency <A class=3Dmw-redirect =
title=3DNIST=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIST">NIST</A> (National Institute =
of=20
Standards and Technology). This version is now often referred to as=20
<I>SHA-0</I>. It was withdrawn by <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DNSA=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA">NSA</A> shortly after =
publication and=20
was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB =
180-1 and=20
commonly referred to as <I>SHA-1</I>. SHA-1 differs from SHA-0 only by a =
single=20
bitwise rotation in the message schedule of its <A=20
title=3D"One-way compression function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_compression_function">compre=
ssion=20
function</A>; this was done, according to NSA, to correct a flaw in the =
original=20
algorithm which reduced its cryptographic security. However, NSA did not =
provide=20
any further explanation or identify the flaw that was corrected. =
Weaknesses have=20
subsequently been reported in both SHA-0 and SHA-1. SHA-1 appears to =
provide=20
greater resistance to attacks<SUP style=3D"WHITE-SPACE: nowrap"=20
class=3DTemplate-Fact>[<I><A title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed"><SPAN=20
title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources from August =
2012">citation=20
needed</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP>, supporting the NSA=E2=80=99s assertion =
that the change=20
increased the security.</P>
<P><BR style=3D"CLEAR: both"></P>
