<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Applications"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D3">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DApplications class=3Dmw-headline>Applications</SPAN></H2>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Cryptography"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D4">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DCryptography class=3Dmw-headline>Cryptography</SPAN></H3>
<DIV class=3D"rellink boilerplate seealso">For more details on this =
topic, see <A=20
title=3D"Cryptographic hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_hash_function#Applicat=
ions">Cryptographic=20
hash function#Applications</A>.</DIV>
<P>SHA-1 forms part of several widely used security applications and =
protocols,=20
including <A title=3D"Transport Layer Security"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security">TLS</A> =
and <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Secure Sockets Layer"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Sockets_Layer">SSL</A>, <A=20
title=3D"Pretty Good Privacy"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretty_Good_Privacy">PGP</A>, <A=20
title=3D"Secure Shell" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell">SSH</A>,=20
<A title=3DS/MIME =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S/MIME">S/MIME</A>, and <A=20
title=3DIPsec href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPsec">IPsec</A>. =
Those=20
applications can also use <A title=3DMD5=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A>; both MD5 and SHA-1 =
are=20
descended from <A title=3DMD4 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD4">MD4</A>.=20
SHA-1 hashing is also used in <A title=3D"Distributed revision control"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distributed_revision_control">distri=
buted=20
revision control</A> systems such as <A title=3D"Git (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_(software)">Git</A>, <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"Mercurial (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercurial_(software)">Mercurial</A>,=
 and <A=20
title=3D"Monotone (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotone_(software)">Monotone</A> =
to identify=20
revisions, and to detect <A title=3D"Data corruption"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_corruption">data =
corruption</A> or=20
tampering. The algorithm has also been used on <A title=3DNintendo=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo">Nintendo's</A> <A =
title=3DWii=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wii">Wii</A> gaming console for =
signature=20
verification when <A title=3DBooting=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Booting">booting</A>, but a =
significant=20
implementation flaw allows for an attacker to bypass the system's =
security=20
scheme.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-7 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-7"><SPAN>[</SPAN>7<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>SHA-1 and SHA-2 are the secure hash algorithms required by law for =
use in=20
certain <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"U.S. Government"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Government">U.S. =
Government</A>=20
applications, including use within other cryptographic algorithms and =
protocols,=20
for the protection of sensitive unclassified information. FIPS PUB 180-1 =
also=20
encouraged adoption and use of SHA-1 by private and commercial =
organizations.=20
SHA-1 is being retired from most government uses; the U.S. National =
Institute of=20
Standards and Technology said, "Federal agencies <I><B>should</B></I> =
stop using=20
SHA-1 for...applications that require collision resistance as soon as =
practical,=20
and must use the <A title=3DSHA-2=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A> family of hash =
functions for=20
these applications after 2010" (emphasis in original).,<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-8=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-8"><SPAN>[</SPAN>8<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
though that was later relaxed.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-9 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-9"><SPAN>[</SPAN>9<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>A prime motivation for the publication of the Secure Hash Algorithm =
was the=20
<A title=3D"Digital Signature Algorithm"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_Signature_Algorithm">Digital=
=20
Signature Standard</A>, in which it is incorporated.</P>
<P>The SHA hash functions have been used as the basis for the <A =
title=3DSHACAL=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHACAL">SHACAL</A> <A =
title=3D"Block cipher"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_cipher">block =
ciphers</A>.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Data Integrity" =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D5">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DData_Integrity class=3Dmw-headline>Data Integrity</SPAN></H3>
<P>The source control management system <A title=3D"Git (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_(software)">Git</A> uses SHA-1 =
not for=20
security but for ensuring that the data has not changed. Linus Torvalds =
has=20
said, "Git uses SHA-1 in a way which has nothing at all to do with =
security....=20
It's just the best hash you can get.... It's about the ability to trust =
your=20
data. I guarantee you, if you put your data in Git, you can trust the =
fact that=20
five years later, after it was converted from a hard disk to a DVD to =
whatever=20
new technology and you copied it, five years later you can verify that =
the data=20
that you get back out is the exact same data you put in."<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-10=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-10"><SPAN>[</SPAN>10<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Cryptanalysis and validation"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D6">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DCryptanalysis_and_validation =
class=3Dmw-headline>Cryptanalysis and=20
validation</SPAN></H2>
<P>For a hash function for which <I>L</I> is the number of bits in the =
message=20
digest, finding a message that corresponds to a given message digest can =
always=20
be done using a brute force search in 2<SUP><I>L</I></SUP> evaluations. =
This is=20
called a <A title=3D"Preimage attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preimage_attack">preimage =
attack</A> and may=20
or may not be practical depending on <I>L</I> and the particular =
computing=20
environment. The second criterion, finding two different messages that =
produce=20
the same message digest, known as a <I>collision,</I> requires on =
average only=20
2<SUP><I>L</I> / 2</SUP> evaluations using a <A title=3D"Birthday =
attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birthday_attack">birthday =
attack</A>. For the=20
latter reason the strength of a hash function is usually compared to a =
symmetric=20
cipher of half the message digest length. Thus SHA-1 was originally =
thought to=20
have 80-bit strength.</P>
<P>Cryptographers have produced collision pairs for SHA-0 and have found =

algorithms that should produce SHA-1 collisions in far fewer than the =
originally=20
expected 2<SUP>80</SUP> evaluations.</P>
<P>In terms of practical security, a major concern about these new =
attacks is=20
that they might pave the way to more efficient ones. Whether this is the =
case is=20
yet to be seen, but a migration to stronger hashes is believed to be =
prudent.=20
Some of the applications that use cryptographic hashes, such as password =

storage, are only minimally affected by a collision attack. Constructing =
a=20
password that works for a given account requires a <A title=3D"Preimage =
attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preimage_attack">preimage =
attack</A>, as well=20
as access to the hash of the original password, which may or may not be =
trivial.=20
Reversing password encryption (e.g. to obtain a password to try against =
a user's=20
account elsewhere) is not made possible by the attacks. (However, even a =
secure=20
password hash can't prevent brute-force attacks on <A title=3D"Password =
strength"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Password_strength">weak =
passwords</A>.)</P>
<P>In the case of document signing, an attacker could not simply fake a=20
signature from an existing document=E2=80=94the attacker would have to =
produce a pair of=20
documents, one innocuous and one damaging, and get the private key =
holder to=20
sign the innocuous document. There are practical circumstances in which =
this is=20
possible; until the end of 2008, it was possible to create forged <A=20
title=3D"Transport Layer Security"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security">SSL</A>=20
certificates using an <A title=3DMD5=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A> collision.<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-11=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-11"><SPAN>[</SPAN>11<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>Due to the block and iterative structure of the algorithms and the =
absence of=20
additional final steps, all SHA functions are vulnerable to <A=20
title=3D"Length extension attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length_extension_attack">length-exte=
nsion</A>=20
and partial-message collision attacks.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-12 =
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-12"><SPAN>[</SPAN>12<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
These attacks allow an attacker to forge a message, signed only by a =
keyed hash=20
- <IMG class=3Dtex alt=3D"SHA(message || key)"=20
src=3D"http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/f/7/df709c16c8657b8c14e2e984cd4=
a6eaf.png">=20
or <IMG class=3Dtex alt=3D"SHA(key || message )"=20
src=3D"http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/f/8af724c844bc811d421f5e74d72=
f0866.png">=20
- by extending the message and recalculating the hash without knowing =
the key.=20
The simplest improvement to prevent these attacks is to hash twice - =
<IMG=20
class=3Dtex alt=3D"SHA_d(message) =3D SHA(SHA(0^b || message))"=20
src=3D"http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/8/a/48a4bea076e8a79bd9bea8ec254=
afdca.png">=20
(<IMG class=3Dtex alt=3D0^b=20
src=3D"http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/e/6/6e609e020d9fa8f8d54b571853b=
70838.png">=20
- zero block, length is equal to block size of hash function).</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Cracking"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D7">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DCracking class=3Dmw-headline>Cracking</SPAN></H3>
<P>The use of plain or salted hashes for password storage is a bad idea, =
they=20
are not designed for this, and key-derivation algorithms like <A =
title=3DPBKDF2=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PBKDF2">PBKDF2</A> or <A =
title=3DBcrypt=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bcrypt">Bcrypt</A> or similar =
should be used=20
instead. "Hashcat", for example, can brute-force over 3bn keys/sec on a=20
GPU-enabled platform,<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-13 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-13"><SPAN>[</SPAN>13<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
which is enough to break many passwords in just a few seconds, with or =
without=20
salt.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-14 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-14"><SPAN>[</SPAN>14<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP><SUP=20
style=3D"WHITE-SPACE: nowrap" class=3D"noprint Inline-Template">[<I><A=20
title=3DWikipedia:Verifiability=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability"><SPAN=20
title=3D"The material in the vicinity of this tag failed verification of =
its source citation(s) from January 2013">not=20
in citation given</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: SHA-0"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D8">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DSHA-0 class=3Dmw-headline>SHA-0</SPAN></H3>
<P>At <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"CRYPTO (conference)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CRYPTO_(conference)">CRYPTO</A> 98, =
two=20
French researchers, <A class=3Dnew title=3D"Florent Chabaud (page does =
not exist)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFlorent_Chabaud&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1">Florent=20
Chabaud</A> and <A class=3Dnew title=3D"Antoine Joux (page does not =
exist)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAntoine_Joux&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1">Antoine=20
Joux</A>, presented an attack on SHA-0 (<A class=3D"external text"=20
href=3D"http://fchabaud.free.fr/English/Publications/sha.pdf" =
rel=3Dnofollow>Chabaud=20
and Joux, 1998</A>): <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Hash collision"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_collision">collisions</A> can =
be found=20
with complexity 2<SUP>61</SUP>, fewer than the 2<SUP>80</SUP> for an =
ideal hash=20
function of the same size.</P>
<P>In 2004, <A title=3D"Eli Biham"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eli_Biham">Biham</A> and Chen found =

near-collisions for SHA-0=E2=80=94two messages that hash to nearly the =
same value; in=20
this case, 142 out of the 160 bits are equal. They also found full =
collisions of=20
SHA-0 reduced to 62 out of its 80 rounds.</P>
<P>Subsequently, on 12 August 2004, a collision for the full SHA-0 =
algorithm was=20
announced by Joux, Carribault, Lemuet, and Jalby. This was done by using =
a=20
generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack. Finding the collision had =

complexity 2<SUP>51</SUP> and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a <A=20
title=3DSupercomputer=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercomputer">supercomputer</A> =
with 256 <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Itanium 2"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Itanium_2">Itanium 2</A> =
processors.=20
(Equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the computer.)</P>
<P>On 17 August 2004, at the Rump Session of CRYPTO 2004, preliminary =
results=20
were announced by <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Xiaoyun Wang"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xiaoyun_Wang">Wang</A>, Feng, Lai, =
and Yu,=20
about an attack on <A title=3DMD5 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A>,=20
SHA-0 and other hash functions. The complexity of their attack on SHA-0 =
is=20
2<SUP>40</SUP>, significantly better than the attack by Joux <I>et =
al.</I><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-15 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-15"><SPAN>[</SPAN>15<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-16 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-16"><SPAN>[</SPAN>16<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>In February 2005, an attack by Xiaoyun Wang, Yiqun Lisa Yin, and =
Hongbo Yu=20
was announced which could find collisions in SHA-0 in 2<SUP>39</SUP>=20
operations.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-autogenerated1_17-0 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-autogenerated1-17"><SPAN>[</SPAN>17<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></S=
UP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-18 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-18"><SPAN>[</SPAN>18<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P><BR>In light of the results for SHA-0, some experts suggested that =
plans for=20
the use of SHA-1 in new <A title=3DCryptosystem=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptosystem">cryptosystems</A> =
should be=20
reconsidered. After the CRYPTO 2004 results were published, NIST =
announced that=20
they planned to phase out the use of SHA-1 by 2010 in favor of the SHA-2 =

variants.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-19 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-19"><SPAN>[</SPAN>19<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>In early 2005, <A title=3D"Vincent Rijmen"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vincent_Rijmen">Rijmen</A> and <A =
class=3Dnew=20
title=3D"Elisabeth Oswald (page does not exist)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElisabeth_Oswald&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1">Oswald</A>=20
published an attack on a reduced version of SHA-1=E2=80=9453 out of 80 =
rounds=E2=80=94which=20
finds collisions with a computational effort of fewer than =
2<SUP>80</SUP>=20
operations.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-20 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-20"><SPAN>[</SPAN>20<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>In February 2005, an attack by <A class=3Dmw-redirect =
title=3D"Xiaoyun Wang"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xiaoyun_Wang">Xiaoyun Wang</A>, <A =
class=3Dnew=20
title=3D"Yiqun Lisa Yin (page does not exist)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYiqun_Lisa_Yin&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1">Yiqun=20
Lisa Yin</A>, and <A class=3Dnew title=3D"Hongbo Yu (page does not =
exist)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHongbo_Yu&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;redlink=3D1">Hongbo=20
Yu</A> was announced.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-autogenerated1_17-1 =
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-autogenerated1-17"><SPAN>[</SPAN>17<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></S=
UP>=20
The attacks can find collisions in the full version of SHA-1, requiring =
fewer=20
than 2<SUP>69</SUP> operations. (A <A title=3D"Brute-force search"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute-force_search">brute-force =
search</A>=20
would require 2<SUP>80</SUP> operations.)</P>
<P>The authors write: "In particular, our analysis is built upon the =
original=20
differential attack on SHA-0 [<I><A title=3DSic=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sic">sic</A></I>], the near =
collision attack=20
on SHA-0, the multiblock collision techniques, as well as the message=20
modification techniques used in the collision search attack on MD5. =
Breaking=20
SHA-1 would not be possible without these powerful analytical =
techniques."<SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-21 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-21"><SPAN>[</SPAN>21<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
The authors have presented a collision for 58-round SHA-1, found with=20
2<SUP>33</SUP> hash operations. The paper with the full attack =
description was=20
published in August 2005 at the CRYPTO conference.</P>
<P>In an interview, Yin states that, "Roughly, we exploit the following =
two=20
weaknesses: One is that the file preprocessing step is not complicated =
enough;=20
another is that certain math operations in the first 20 rounds have =
unexpected=20
security problems."<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-22 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-22"><SPAN>[</SPAN>22<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>On 17 August 2005, an improvement on the SHA-1 attack was announced =
on behalf=20
of Xiaoyun Wang, <A title=3D"Andrew Yao"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Yao">Andrew Yao</A> and <A=20
title=3D"Frances Yao" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frances_Yao">Frances=20
Yao</A> at the CRYPTO 2005 rump session, lowering the complexity =
required for=20
finding a collision in SHA-1 to 2<SUP>63</SUP>.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-23=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-23"><SPAN>[</SPAN>23<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
On 18 December 2007 the details of this result were explained and =
verified by=20
Martin Cochran.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-24 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-24"><SPAN>[</SPAN>24<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>Christophe De Canni=C3=A8re and Christian Rechberger further improved =
the attack=20
on SHA-1 in "Finding SHA-1 Characteristics: General Results and=20
Applications,"<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-25 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-25"><SPAN>[</SPAN>25<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
receiving the Best Paper Award at <A class=3Dmw-redirect =
title=3DASIACRYPT=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASIACRYPT">ASIACRYPT</A> 2006. A =
two-block=20
collision for 64-round SHA-1 was presented, found using unoptimized =
methods with=20
2<SUP>35</SUP> compression function evaluations. As this attack requires =
the=20
equivalent of about 2<SUP>35</SUP> evaluations, it is considered to be a =

significant theoretical break.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-26 class=3Dreference><A =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-26"><SPAN>[</SPAN>26<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
Their attack was extended further to 73 rounds (of 80) in 2010 by=20
Grechnikov.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-27 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-27"><SPAN>[</SPAN>27<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
In order to find an actual collision in the full 80 rounds of the hash =
function,=20
however, massive amounts of computer time are required. To that end, a =
collision=20
search for SHA-1 using the distributed computing platform <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3DBOINC href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BOINC">BOINC</A> =
began August 8,=20
2007, organized by the <A title=3D"Graz University of Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graz_University_of_Technology">Graz =

University of Technology</A>. The effort was abandoned May 12, 2009 due =
to lack=20
of progress.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-28 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-28"><SPAN>[</SPAN>28<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>At the Rump Session of CRYPTO 2006, Christian Rechberger and =
Christophe De=20
Canni=C3=A8re claimed to have discovered a collision attack on SHA-1 =
that would allow=20
an attacker to select at least parts of the message.<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-29=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-29"><SPAN>[</SPAN>29<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-30 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-30"><SPAN>[</SPAN>30<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>In 2008, an attack methodology by St=C3=A9phane Manuel reported hash =
collisions=20
with an estimated theoretical complexity of 2<SUP>51</SUP> to =
2<SUP>57</SUP>=20
operations.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-31 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-31"><SPAN>[</SPAN>31<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
However he later retracted that claim after finding that local collision =
paths=20
were not actually independent, and finally quoting as the most efficient =
a=20
collision vector that was already known before this work.<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-32=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-32"><SPAN>[</SPAN>32<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>Cameron McDonald, Philip Hawkes and Josef Pieprzyk presented a hash =
collision=20
attack with claimed complexity 2<SUP>52</SUP> at the Rump session of =
Eurocrypt=20
2009.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-33 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-33"><SPAN>[</SPAN>33<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
However, the accompanying paper, "Differential Path for SHA-1 with =
complexity <A=20
title=3D"Big O notation"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation"><I>O</I></A>(2<SUP>5=
2</SUP>)"=20
has been withdrawn due to the authors' discovery that their estimate was =

incorrect.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-34 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-34"><SPAN>[</SPAN>34<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP></P>
<P>As of 2012, the most efficient attack against SHA-1 is considered to =
be the=20
one by Marc Stevens with an estimated cost of $2.77M to break a single =
hash=20
value by renting CPU power from cloud servers.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-35=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-35"><SPAN>[</SPAN>35<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
Stevens developed this attack in a project called HashClash,<SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-36=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-36"><SPAN>[</SPAN>36<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
implementing a differential path attack. On 8 November 2010, he claimed =
he had a=20
fully working near-collision attack against full SHA-1 working with an =
estimated=20
complexity equivalent to 2<SUP>57.5</SUP> SHA-1 compressions. He =
estimates this=20
attack can be extended to a full collision with a complexity around=20
2<SUP>61</SUP>.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Official =
validation"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D9">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DOfficial_validation class=3Dmw-headline>Official =
validation</SPAN></H3>
<DIV class=3D"rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <A=20
title=3D"Cryptographic Module Validation Program"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_Module_Validation_Prog=
ram">Cryptographic=20
Module Validation Program</A></DIV>
<P>Implementations of all FIPS-approved security functions can be =
officially=20
validated through the <A title=3D"Cryptographic Module Validation =
Program"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_Module_Validation_Prog=
ram">CMVP=20
program</A>, jointly run by the <A=20
title=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_=
Technology">National=20
Institute of Standards and Technology</A> (NIST) and the <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"Communications Security Establishment"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communications_Security_Establishmen=
t">Communications=20
Security Establishment</A> (CSE). For informal verification, a package =
to=20
generate a high number of test vectors is made available for download on =
the=20
NIST site; the resulting verification however does not replace, in any =
way, the=20
formal CMVP validation, which is required by law for certain =
applications.</P>
<P>As of February 2011<SUP style=3D"DISPLAY: none"=20
class=3D"plainlinks noprint asof-tag update"><A class=3D"external text"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it">[update]</A></SUP>,=20
there are nearly 1400 validated implementations of SHA-1, with around a =
dozen of=20
them capable of handling messages with a length in bits not a multiple =
of eight=20
(see <A class=3D"external text"=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/shs/shaval.htm"=20
rel=3Dnofollow>SHS Validation List</A>).</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Examples and =
pseudocode"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D10">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DExamples_and_pseudocode class=3Dmw-headline>Examples and=20
pseudocode</SPAN></H2>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Example hashes" =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D11">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DExample_hashes class=3Dmw-headline>Example hashes</SPAN></H3>
<P>These are examples of SHA-1 digests. <A title=3DASCII=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII">ASCII</A> encoding is used =
for all=20
messages.</P><PRE>SHA1("<A title=3D"The quick brown fox jumps over the =
lazy dog" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_quick_brown_fox_jumps_over_the_l=
azy_dog">The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog</A>")
=3D 2fd4e1c6 7a2d28fc ed849ee1 bb76e739 1b93eb12
</PRE>
<P>Even a small change in the message will, with overwhelming =
probability,=20
result in a completely different hash due to the <A title=3D"Avalanche =
effect"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avalanche_effect">avalanche =
effect</A>. For=20
example, changing <CODE>dog</CODE> to <CODE>cog</CODE> produces a hash =
with=20
different values for 81 of the 160 bits:</P><PRE>SHA1("The quick brown =
fox jumps over the lazy <B>c</B>og")
=3D de9f2c7f d25e1b3a fad3e85a 0bd17d9b 100db4b3

</PRE>
<P>The hash of the zero-length string is:</P><PRE>SHA1("")
=3D da39a3ee 5e6b4b0d 3255bfef 95601890 afd80709
</PRE>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: SHA-1 =
pseudocode"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D12">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DSHA-1_pseudocode class=3Dmw-headline>SHA-1 =
pseudocode</SPAN></H3>
<P><A title=3DPseudocode=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudocode">Pseudocode</A> for the =
SHA-1=20
algorithm follows:</P><PRE><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Note 1: All =
variables are unsigned 32 bits and wrap modulo 2<SUP>32</SUP> when =
calculating</I></SPAN>
<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Note 2: All constants in this pseudo =
code are in <A title=3DEndianness =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endianness">big =
endian</A>.</I></SPAN>=20
        <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Within each word, the most =
significant byte is stored in the leftmost byte position</I></SPAN>

<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Initialize variables:</I></SPAN>
h0 =3D 0x67452301
h1 =3D 0xEFCDAB89
h2 =3D 0x98BADCFE
h3 =3D 0x10325476
h4 =3D 0xC3D2E1F0

<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Pre-processing:</I></SPAN>
append the bit '1' to the message
append 0 =E2=89=A4 k &lt; 512 bits '0', so that the resulting message =
length (in <I>bits</I>)
   is <A title=3D"Modular arithmetic" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic">congruent</A> =
to 448 (mod 512)
append length of message (before pre-processing), in <I>bits</I>, as =
64-bit <A title=3DEndianness =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endianness">big-endian</A> integer

<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Process the message in successive =
512-bit chunks:</I></SPAN>
break message into 512-bit chunks
<B>for</B> each chunk
    break chunk into sixteen 32-bit big-endian words w[i], 0 =E2=89=A4 i =
=E2=89=A4 15

    <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Extend the sixteen 32-bit words into =
eighty 32-bit words:</I></SPAN>
    <B>for</B> i <B>from</B> 16 to 79
        w[i] =3D (w[i-3] <B>xor</B> w[i-8] <B>xor</B> w[i-14] <B>xor</B> =
w[i-16]) <B><A title=3D"Circular shift" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_shift">leftrotate</A></B> =
1

    <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Initialize hash value for this =
chunk:</I></SPAN>
    a =3D h0
    b =3D h1
    c =3D h2
    d =3D h3
    e =3D h4

    <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Main loop:</I></SPAN><SUP =
id=3Dcite_ref-37 class=3Dreference><A =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-37"><SPAN>[</SPAN>37<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>
    <B>for</B> i <B>from</B> 0 <B>to</B> 79
        <B>if</B> 0 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 19 <B>then</B>
            f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>or</B> ((<B>not</B> b) <B>and</B> =
d)
            k =3D 0x5A827999
        <B>else if</B> 20 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 39
            f =3D b <B>xor</B> c <B>xor</B> d
            k =3D 0x6ED9EBA1
        <B>else if</B> 40 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 59
            f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>or</B> (b <B>and</B> d) <B>or</B> =
(c <B>and</B> d)=20
            k =3D 0x8F1BBCDC
        <B>else if</B> 60 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 79
            f =3D b <B>xor</B> c <B>xor</B> d
            k =3D 0xCA62C1D6

        temp =3D (a <B>leftrotate</B> 5) + f + e + k + w[i]
        e =3D d
        d =3D c
        c =3D b <B>leftrotate</B> 30
        b =3D a
        a =3D temp

    <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Add this chunk's hash to result so =
far:</I></SPAN>
    h0 =3D h0 + a
    h1 =3D h1 + b=20
    h2 =3D h2 + c
    h3 =3D h3 + d
    h4 =3D h4 + e

<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>Produce the final hash value =
(big-endian):</I></SPAN>
digest =3D hash =3D h0 <B>append</B> h1 <B>append</B> h2 <B>append</B> =
h3 <B>append</B> h4
</PRE>
<P>The constant values used are chosen as <A title=3D"Nothing up my =
sleeve number"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nothing_up_my_sleeve_number">nothing=
 up my=20
sleeve numbers</A>: the four round constants <CODE>k</CODE> are =
2<SUP>30</SUP>=20
times the square roots of 2, 3, 5 and 10. The first four starting values =
for=20
<CODE>h0</CODE> through <CODE>h3</CODE> are the same as the MD5 =
algorithm, and=20
the fifth (for <CODE>h4</CODE>) is similar.</P>
<P>Instead of the formulation from the original FIPS PUB 180-1 shown, =
the=20
following equivalent expressions may be used to compute <CODE>f</CODE> =
in the=20
main loop above:</P><PRE>(0  =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 19): f =3D d =
<B>xor</B> (b <B>and</B> (c <B>xor</B> d))                <SPAN =
style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>(alternative 1)</I></SPAN>
(0  =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 19): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>xor</B> =
((<B>not</B> b) <B>and</B> d)          <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
green"><I>(alternative 2)</I></SPAN>
(0  =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 19): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) + ((<B>not</B> b) =
<B>and</B> d)            <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>(alternative =
3)</I></SPAN>
(0  =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 19): f =3D vec_sel(d, c, b)                    =
   <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>(alternative 4)</I></SPAN>
=20
(40 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 59): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>or</B> (d =
<B>and</B> (b <B>or</B> c))          <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
green"><I>(alternative 1)</I></SPAN>
(40 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 59): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>or</B> (d =
<B>and</B> (b <B>xor</B> c))         <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
green"><I>(alternative 2)</I></SPAN>
(40 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 59): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) + (d <B>and</B> (b =
<B>xor</B> c))          <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: green"><I>(alternative =
3)</I></SPAN>
(40 =E2=89=A4 i =E2=89=A4 59): f =3D (b <B>and</B> c) <B>xor</B> (b =
<B>and</B> d) <B>xor</B> (c <B>and</B> d)  <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
green"><I>(alternative 4)</I></SPAN>
</PRE>
<P>Max Locktyukhin has also shown<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-38 =
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;oldid=3D538=
112650#cite_note-38"><SPAN>[</SPAN>38<SPAN>]</SPAN></A></SUP>=20
that for the rounds 32=E2=80=9379 the computation of:</P><PRE>      w[i] =
=3D (w[i-3] <B>xor</B> w[i-8] <B>xor</B> w[i-14] <B>xor</B> w[i-16]) =
<B><A title=3D"Circular shift" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_shift">leftrotate</A></B> =
1
</PRE>
<P>can be replaced with:</P><PRE>      w[i] =3D (w[i-6] <B>xor</B> =
w[i-16] <B>xor</B> w[i-28] <B>xor</B> w[i-32]) <B><A title=3D"Circular =
shift" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_shift">leftrotate</A></B> =
2
</PRE>
<P>This transformation keeps all operands 64-bit aligned and, by =
removing the=20
dependency of <CODE>w[i]</CODE> on <CODE>w[i-3]</CODE>, allows efficient =
SIMD=20
implementation with a vector length of 4 such as <A title=3DX86=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86">x86</A> <A=20
title=3D"Streaming SIMD Extensions"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streaming_SIMD_Extensions">SSE</A>=20
instructions.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Use of SHA-1 in MS Office password protection"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSHA-1&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D13">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DUse_of_SHA-1_in_MS_Office_password_protection =
class=3Dmw-headline>Use of=20
SHA-1 in MS Office password protection</SPAN></H2>
<DIV class=3D"rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"Microsoft Office password protection"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Office_password_protection=
">Microsoft=20
Office password protection</A></DIV>
<P>SHA-1 was first used in <A title=3D"Microsoft Office 2007"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Office_2007">Microsoft =
Office=20
2007</A>. Before a password-protected <A title=3DWord=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word">Word</A>, <A title=3DExcel=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Excel">Excel</A>, and <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3DPowerPoint =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PowerPoint">PowerPoint</A>=20
document is opened, 50000 conversions of a password to a 128-bit <A=20
title=3D"Key (cryptography)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_(cryptography)">key</A> occur. =
It=20
considerably slows down <A title=3D"Brute-force attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute-force_attack">brute-force =
attack</A>=20
speed and therefore chances to open the password-protected document =
decline as=20
well. SHA-1 conversions are only used when a password to <I>open</I> =
document is=20
set since it is the only password type that features document <A=20
title=3DEncryption =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encryption">encryption</A>.=20
In <A title=3D"Microsoft Office 2010"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Office_2010">Microsoft =
Office=20
2010</A> a number of SHA-1 conversions was doubled and comprises =
100000.</P>
